Here's how to implement all three:

**1 & 2 — Guard navigation in `AppShell.xaml.cs`:**

```csharp
protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
{
    base.OnNavigating(args);

    // Only intercept back navigation from EditProductPage
    if (args.Source == ShellNavigationSource.Pop &&
        Shell.Current.CurrentPage is EditProductPage page &&
        page.HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

        bool discard = await Shell.Current.CurrentPage.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!discard)
            args.Cancel();

        deferral.Complete();
    }
}
```

> **Key:** You must call `GetDeferral()` before the `await` and `deferral.Complete()` after — otherwise the navigation completes before your async dialog returns.

**3 — Custom "Cancel" back button in `EditProductPage.xaml`:**

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.Views.EditProductPage"
             Title="Edit Product">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                           Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- your form content -->
</ContentPage>
```

And in your ViewModel (or code-behind):

```csharp
[RelayCommand]
async Task Cancel()
{
    // This triggers a Pop, which OnNavigating will intercept
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
}
```

**How it works together:**
- Tapping the "Cancel" button fires `CancelCommand` → calls `GoToAsync("..")` → triggers `OnNavigating` with `ShellNavigationSource.Pop` → your guard shows the dialog → navigation is cancelled or allowed.
- The hardware/swipe back gesture also triggers the same `OnNavigating` guard automatically.
